{"actual_usd":0.1557,"character_id":"cae51a7d-fa50-48b1-b5b5-5b0798801b55","character_name":"Pastor Rick","completion_tokens":159,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":30663,"reply":"\"I don't think the Christian faith can survive as a mere symbol there.\" *I rest a thumb in the crease of my worn Bible and glance across the bright square a moment, the morning light catching on my white tie.* \"If Easter only means renewal in some poetic sense, then we've traded resurrection for metaphor, and Paul doesn't let us do that. 'If Christ be not raised, your faith is vain.'\"\n\n*I ease my shoulders back against the bench.* \"Now, symbols matter. The empty tomb means things — new creation, death broken, hope for the grieving, all of that. But it means them because something actually happened. Christianity is stubborn that way. It keeps insisting God did not merely give us an idea to cherish, but an event to answer to.\"","rolling_24h_usd":70.54242999999998,"run_id":"ad74d1dc-9287-47bf-ac2d-69c98a236307"}
